e foundation, the source, and the seed. With a focus on this concept’s history in France and Germany, Wampole traces its influence in diverse areas such as the search for the mystical origins of words, land worship, and nationalist rhetoric, including the disturbing portrayal of the Jews as an unrooted, and thus unrighteous, people. Exploring the works of Martin Heidegger, Simone Weil, Jean-Paul Sartre, Paul Celan, and many more, Rootedness is a groundbreaking study of a figure of speech that has had wide-reaching—and at times dire—political and social consequences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAffiliation (Philosophy) 0aAffiliation (Philosophy). 0aAlienation (Philosophy) 0aAlienation (Philosophy). 0aFrench literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGerman literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMetaphor in literature. 0aRoots (Botany) in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  afrench, france, philosophy, philosophical, language, metaphor, communication, ecology, literature, literary studies, history, historical, political science, politics, 20th century, europe, european, family tree, roots, rooted, familial connections, germany, german, words, land ownership, nationalism, antisemitism, paul celan, martin heidegger, jean-paul sartre, simone weil, narratives, alienation, affiliation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022631765640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226317793423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226317793/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles